        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Payables Overview",
            Slug = "payables-overview",
            Summary = "What Accounts Payable covers: vendor bills, vendor payments, the bill lifecycle, payment application, and how payables connect to Purchase Orders and Vendors.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/payables"]""",
            Tags = """["payables","ap","accounting"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payables Overview\n\nPayables is your Accounts Payable (AP) workspace — the desk where you handle every dollar the shop owes its vendors. You enter the **vendor bills** that come in, record the **vendor payments** that go out, and apply each payment against the bills it pays down. Payables ties into Purchase Orders (so you can match a bill to what was ordered and received) and to Vendors (every bill and every payment belongs to one vendor).\n\nThe page is split into tabs — **Bills**, **Payments**, **Batches**, and **Accounts** — with a vendor filter and a status filter across the top to narrow what you are looking at.\n\n### What Is a Vendor Bill?\n\nA vendor bill is an invoice you owe a vendor. Each bill carries:\n- A **Bill Number**, assigned for you\n- The **Vendor** it is owed to\n- The **Vendor Invoice #** — the vendor's own number, so you can match it to the paper invoice\n- A **Bill Date** and a **Due Date**\n- One or more **Line Items** (description, quantity, unit price)\n- An optional **Tax Amount**\n- A **Status** telling you where the bill stands\n- The running **Total**, the amount **Paid**, and the **Balance Due**\n\nYou can enter a bill two ways. Type it in **by hand** — add the lines yourself from the paper invoice. Or bill it **From a Purchase Order** — pick the PO and bill against the lines you have already received. In PO mode you can only bill quantity that was received but not yet billed. That guardrail is **three-way matching**: the PO, the receipt, and the invoice all have to agree before you pay.\n\n### Bill Lifecycle\n\nA vendor bill moves through these stages:\n\n1. **Draft** — Entered but not yet approved. Every new bill starts here. Nothing is owed and no payment can be applied yet.\n2. **Approved** — You have approved it for payment. Use the **Approve Bill** button on a Draft bill. Once approved, it is payable and it ages toward its due date.\n3. **Partially Paid** — Approved, and one or more payments have paid down part of it. There is still a balance left.\n4. **Paid** — Fully paid off. Balance Due is zero.\n5. **Void** — Cancelled before it was paid. You can void a bill only while it is Draft or Approved, only when nothing has been paid against it, and only when it did not come from an expense.\n\n### What Is a Vendor Payment?\n\nA vendor payment records money you sent a vendor and which of that vendor's bills it pays. Each payment carries:\n- A **Payment #**, assigned for you\n- The **Vendor**\n- A **Method** (Cash, Check, Credit Card, Bank Transfer, Wire, or Other)\n- An **Amount**\n- A **Payment Date**\n- An optional **Reference #** (check number, wire reference, and the like)\n- One or more **applications** that spread the payment across open bills\n\nWhen you start a payment, you pick the vendor and the panel lists that vendor's open bills (the Approved and Partially Paid ones). You type how much of the payment goes against each bill. The amounts you apply cannot add up to more than the payment; anything you have not assigned yet shows as **Unapplied**. As you apply the payment, each bill moves toward Partially Paid or Paid on its own.\n\n### Electronic Payments and Their Bank Status\n\nElectronic payments — Bank Transfer and Wire — show a **bank status** that tells you how far the payment has gotten with the bank: Queued, Retrying, Succeeded, Failed, or Cancelled. If a send fails, a banner appears at the top of the page and on the bill and payment, and you can **Retry** it. A wire adds one more control: while it is Queued, a second person must **Attest** it — confirm it is legitimate — before it goes out. That second set of eyes on outgoing wires is a deliberate safeguard against fraud and mistakes.\n\n### How Payables Ties to the Rest of Your Work\n\n**Purchase Orders:** Bill a PO and each line is matched to what was received. You can only bill received-but-unbilled quantity, so you never overpay a vendor for goods that never arrived. If the invoice price differs from the PO price, the difference is carried through for you.\n\n**Vendors:** Every bill and payment belongs to one vendor. The vendor name links back to the vendor record, and the vendor filter up top narrows both the Bills and Payments tabs to one vendor at a time.\n\n**Expenses:** When someone submits an expense that a vendor will be paid for, approving that expense turns it into a vendor bill automatically — so it lands in your AP list to be paid like any other bill. It shows a **From Expense** label. You do not void these here; see the Advanced Reference for how to unwind one.\n\n**If your shop uses an outside accounting system:** Payables runs the shop's AP only when it is the sole system of record. If your shop keeps its books in an outside accounting package instead, that package owns Accounts Payable and this module steps aside, so you are never keeping two copies of the same bills.\n\n### Bank Accounts and NACHA Payment Batches (Optional)\n\nIf your shop sends its own ACH payments straight from the bank, two extra tabs appear: **Accounts** and **Batches**. They stay hidden until an administrator turns them on (after your bank's ACH agreement is signed), and only Admin, Manager, and Office Manager can use them.\n\n- The **Accounts** tab holds each vendor's bank account — the routing and account numbers you pay into. The numbers are stored scrambled and shown masked, so nobody can read a full number off the screen. Adding or changing one takes a second person's approval, plus a zero-dollar test entry (a **prenote**) that proves the account is good before you send real money. See the 'Vendor Bank Accounts & Dual Control' module.\n- The **Batches** tab gathers your approved Bank Transfer payments into a **NACHA file** — the standard file your bank's website accepts — which you download and upload to the bank. A second person then releases it. Splitting who builds the file from who releases it means no one person can move money alone. This tab also takes in the bank's return file. See the 'NACHA Payment Batches' module.\n\nIf you do not see these tabs, your shop pays vendors by check, wire, or some other way and does not send ACH files from Forge — that is perfectly normal.\n\n### When to Use Payables\n\n- A vendor invoice arrives — enter it as a bill, then approve it for payment\n- You want the invoice checked against the order — bill it From a Purchase Order so you can only bill what was received\n- You are paying a vendor — record a payment and apply it across that vendor's open bills\n- An electronic payment fails — retry it from the payment\n- A wire needs a second sign-off — attest the queued wire before it goes out","sections":[]}"""
        });

