            Slug = "payables-bank-accounts",
            Summary = "How vendor bank accounts work on the Accounts tab: storing ACH routing/account numbers securely, the dual-control approval, the prenote verification step, and the account lifecycle. Available when an administrator has turned on bank payments.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 7,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/payables/accounts"]""",
            Tags = """["payables","ap","banking","nacha","ach","dual-control"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Vendor Bank Accounts & Dual Control\n\nBefore your shop can pay a vendor by ACH, that vendor needs a verified bank account on file. The **Accounts** tab on the Payables page is where you store, approve, and verify those accounts. This tab appears only when an administrator has turned on bank payments (once the bank's ACH agreement is in place), and only the Admin, Manager, and Office Manager roles can use it.\n\n### Why This Is Different From a Normal Form\n\nBank account numbers are money-moving secrets. Forge treats them very differently from ordinary fields:\n\n- **Stored scrambled, shown masked.** The routing and account numbers you type are stored scrambled and never shown back in full. The table and detail only ever show a **masked** value (for example, the last few digits). Nobody — not even an admin — can read the whole number off the screen.\n- **Re-enter to change.** Because the number is never shown back, changing an account means re-typing **both** numbers from scratch. There is no 'show current number' option — that is on purpose, so a full number is never exposed.\n- **Dual control.** Adding or changing an account does not make it payable. A **second person** has to approve it. Whoever entered or changed the numbers can never be the one who approves them — the system will not let you approve your own work.\n- **Prenote verification.** Even after approval, the account is proven with a real but **zero-dollar** ACH entry — a **prenote** — sent through the bank. Only after the bank's return window passes with no rejection do you mark the account verified. Until then you cannot pay it in a live batch. The prenote is how you catch a fat-fingered routing or account number before any real money rides on it.\n\n### Adding a Vendor Bank Account\n\n1. Go to **Payables → Accounts** and click **New Bank Account**.\n2. Choose the **Vendor** the account belongs to.\n3. Enter a **Nickname** (a label like 'Operating - Wells Fargo' so you can tell multiple accounts apart).\n4. Choose the **Type** — Checking or Savings.\n5. Enter the 9-digit **Routing #** and the **Account #** (4 to 17 digits).\n6. Save. The account is created in **Pending Approval** status. A confirmation reminds you it is awaiting dual-control approval.\n\nWhen you **change** an existing account, the vendor is locked (an account stays with its vendor) and you must re-enter both numbers. Saving the change resets the account back to **Pending Approval** — the prior approval and prenote no longer count.\n\n### The Account Lifecycle\n\nA vendor bank account moves through these statuses, shown as a colored label:\n\n1. **Pending Approval** — Just created or just changed. Not payable. Waiting for a second user to approve.\n2. **Approved** — A different user clicked **Approve (dual control)**. Approval is recorded with who approved it and when. The next step is the prenote.\n3. **Prenote Sent** — A zero-dollar test entry has gone to the bank (built as a prenote batch on the Batches tab). The account is waiting out the bank's return window to see if the bank kicks it back.\n4. **Verified** — The return window passed with no rejection, and someone clicked **Mark verified**. The account is now good to use in live payment batches.\n5. **Disabled** — The account has been turned off. It is excluded from all batches. Re-enabling requires a fresh dual-control approval (and a new prenote).\n\n### Row Actions on the Accounts Tab\n\nEach account row shows the actions that apply to its current status:\n\n- **Approve (dual control)** (check icon) — appears on a Pending Approval account. Must be clicked by someone other than the person who entered the numbers.\n- **Mark verified** (verified icon) — appears on a Prenote Sent account once the bank's return window has passed.\n- **Change numbers** (edit icon) — re-enter both numbers; this resets the account to Pending Approval.\n- **Disable** (block icon) — confirms, then excludes the account from all batches.\n\nA Disabled account shows no edit or disable actions.\n\n### How This Connects to Paying Vendors\n\nThe verified account is the **destination** for ACH payments. When you build a payment batch on the Batches tab, each eligible Bank Transfer payment is matched to its vendor's bank account. A payment whose vendor has no verified account shows a 'Needs verified bank account' warning and cannot be included until you add and verify one.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- Bank numbers are stored scrambled and shown masked — to change one you re-enter it.\n- Every add or change needs a **different** person to approve it (dual control).\n- A **prenote** (zero-dollar test entry) proves the account is good before you pay it.\n- Lifecycle: Pending Approval → Approved → Prenote Sent → Verified (→ Disabled).\n- A vendor needs a Verified account before its ACH payments can go into a batch.","sections":[]}"""
