            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/payables/batches"]""",
            Tags = """["payables","ap","banking","nacha","ach","batches"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## NACHA Payment Batches\n\nWhen your shop originates its own ACH payments, the **Batches** tab on the Payables page is where you turn approved electronic payments into a **NACHA file** — the standard bank-format file you upload to your bank's portal. Like the Accounts tab, Batches appears only when an administrator has turned on bank payments, and only Admin, Manager, and Office Manager roles can use it.\n\n### The Big Picture: Assemble → Generate → Upload → Release\n\nForge does not connect directly to your bank. It produces the file; you upload it; a second person confirms it went out. The flow is deliberately split so no single person can move money alone:\n\n1. **Assemble** — Gather eligible payments into a Draft batch.\n2. **Generate** — Build the NACHA file from the Draft batch.\n3. **Download & upload** — Download the file and upload it to your bank's portal yourself.\n4. **Release** — A **different** person confirms the upload, which marks the payments as sent. This split — one person builds the file, another releases it — is a standard AP control that keeps any one person from moving money alone.\n\n### What Makes a Payment Eligible\n\nA payment is eligible for a batch when it is a **Bank Transfer** (ACH) payment that has not already been batched. When you open the New Batch panel, the system lists every eligible payment with its payment number, vendor, amount, date, and destination account. Payments whose vendor has a **verified** bank account can be selected; a payment whose vendor has no verified account shows a 'Needs verified bank account' warning and cannot be selected until you add and verify one on the Accounts tab.\n\n### Assembling a Batch\n\n1. Go to **Payables → Batches** and click **New Batch**.\n2. Set the **Effective Date** — the date the funds should settle at the bank.\n3. In the eligible-payments list, check each payment to include. The **Selected total** updates as you go.\n4. Click **Assemble Batch**. The batch is created in **Draft** status.\n\n### Generating, Downloading, and Releasing\n\nOn the Batches tab, each row's actions depend on its status:\n\n- **Generate NACHA file** (build icon) — appears on a **Draft** batch. Builds the NACHA file and moves the batch to **Generated**.\n- **Download file** (download icon) — appears on a **Generated** or **Released** batch. Downloads the .ach file for you to upload to the bank portal.\n- **Release** (verified icon) — appears on a **Generated** batch. After you confirm that the file was uploaded to the bank, releasing marks the batch's payments as transmitted. **The release must be done by a different person than the one who built the batch** — the system enforces this, so no one person can both build and send a payment file.\n- **Cancel batch** (block icon) — appears on a **Draft** or **Generated** batch. Cancels it; its payments return to the eligible pool so you can re-batch them.\n\n### Batch Statuses\n\n- **Draft** — Assembled but no file generated yet. Can be generated or cancelled.\n- **Generated** — The NACHA file exists. Can be downloaded, released, or cancelled.\n- **Released** — A second user confirmed the upload; the payments are marked transmitted. Terminal.\n- **Cancelled** — The batch was abandoned; its payments returned to the eligible pool. Terminal.\n\n### Prenote Batches\n\nA **Prenote Batch** is a special batch that verifies bank accounts rather than paying anyone. Click **Prenote Batch**, set an effective date, and assemble it: every approved (not-yet-prenoted) vendor bank account gets a **zero-dollar** verification entry. You generate, download, and upload the prenote file the same way as a payment batch. After the bank's return window passes with no return, go to the Accounts tab and mark those accounts **Verified**. Prenote batches are how an Approved account becomes a Verified, payable account.\n\n### Importing the Bank's Returns / NOC File\n\nBanks send back an ACH **return** file (payments the receiving bank rejected) and **Notification of Change (NOC)** entries (the receiving bank telling you the correct routing/account to use next time). On the Batches tab, click **Import Returns File** and choose the file your bank gave you (.ach, .txt, or .dat). It is safe to import the same file twice — nothing gets double-counted — and the import tells you how many payments came back, how many prenotes were rejected, and how many correction notices were found. Returned payments show up as failed sends so you know to follow up with the vendor.\n\n### Key Takeaways\n\n- Forge builds the NACHA file; you upload it to the bank; a second person releases it.\n- Only un-batched **Bank Transfer** payments are eligible, and only when the vendor has a **verified** account.\n- Batch lifecycle: Draft → Generated → Released (or Cancelled).\n- A **prenote batch** sends zero-dollar test entries to verify accounts.\n- Whoever releases the batch must be a **different person** than whoever built it — so no one moves money alone.\n- Import the bank's **returns / NOC** file to record rejections and account corrections.","sections":[]}"""
        });

