            Tags = """["payables","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payables — Advanced Reference\n\nThe deeper corners of Accounts Payable — the cases you hit once you have been doing this a while. For the day-to-day flow (entering bills, recording payments, the bill lifecycle) start with the Payables Overview, Field Reference, and Walkthrough. This page covers the parts those leave out: paying vendors in another currency, reading a stuck electronic payment, and how an expense turns into a bill you have to pay.\n\n## Paying Vendors in Another Currency\n\nMost shops pay every vendor in one currency, and then none of this shows up — the **Currency** and **FX Rate** fields stay hidden and every amount is in your home currency. These fields only appear when your shop has been set up to buy in more than one currency (say, a supplier who bills in euros).\n\n- A foreign-currency bill carries its **currency** and an **exchange rate** as of the bill date, so the amount can be shown in your home currency too. Leave the currency blank and the bill is simply in your home currency. The rate has to be more than zero.\n- Here is the part that trips people up: the rate moves between the day the bill is dated and the day you actually pay it. So each payment you apply carries its **own** rate — the rate on the day you pay. The gap between the two rates is the **exchange gain or loss** — you paid a little more or a little less than the bill first looked like, purely because the currency moved.\n- That gain or loss is worked out **per bill**, not per payment. One payment that clears three euro bills can show a small gain on one and a small loss on another, depending on each bill's original rate. You enter the rate on the bill and again as you pay each bill; the difference is figured for you.\n- A bill that came from an expense is always in your home currency. Expenses never carry a foreign currency into Payables.\n\n## Reading a Stuck or Failed Electronic Payment\n\nBank Transfer and Wire payments show how far they got with the bank. A cash or check payment leaves all of this blank — there is nothing to send. When an electronic payment is not moving, open it and read these:\n\n- **Status** — Queued, Retrying, Succeeded, Failed, or Cancelled.\n- **Attempts** — how many times the send has been tried, shown next to Retrying.\n- **Next attempt** — when the system will try again on its own, while it is retrying.\n- **Last error** — the reason the most recent try failed. This is your first clue: a bad account number reads differently from a bank outage, and tells you whether to fix something or just wait.\n- **Confirmation reference** — the bank's own reference number, saved once the send goes through. Keep this; it is your proof the money left.\n\nWhen a send fails, a banner appears across the top of both the Bills and Payments tabs and the bill picks up a **Payment Failed** label, so a failed vendor payment never quietly hides. If your shop sends its own electronic payments, there is also a single page that lists every failed payment together, so on a busy day you can work them in one place instead of hunting tab by tab — Admin, Manager, and Office Manager can open it. **Retry** tries a failed or cancelled send again. You cannot retry one that already succeeded — the money is already gone, and retrying would pay the vendor twice.\n\n## When an Expense Becomes a Bill You Have to Pay\n\nThis is the one that surprises new AP clerks: bills can appear in your list that nobody typed. When an employee submits an expense that a **vendor** will be paid for, approving that expense turns it into a vendor bill automatically — so it lands in AP and ages and gets paid like any other bill. Expenses paid in cash, with no vendor, or for nothing do not become bills; those stay on the expense side.\n\n- A bill made this way arrives **already approved** — the approval on the expense is its approval, so it does not sit in Draft waiting for you. It shows a **From Expense** label so you can tell it apart at a glance.\n- **One live bill per expense.** An expense can only ever have one open bill. If someone re-approves the same expense, you get the bill you already had, not a duplicate — so you are not chasing two bills for one receipt.\n- **You do not void a From-Expense bill here.** Its life is tied to the expense. Voiding just the bill would leave the expense still approved with nothing to pay it, which does not add up. To cancel it, send the **expense** back — reject it or ask for a revision — and the bill goes away with it, cleanly.\n- Sending the expense back is **blocked once you have paid against the bill.** You cannot unwind a bill you have already partly paid — reverse the payment or payments first, then send the expense back. Same rule as voiding an ordinary bill: nothing that has been paid can just vanish.\n\n## What Approving a Bill Does — and Does Not — Do Today\n\nApproving a bill makes it real AP work: it is payable, it ages toward its due date, and you can pay it. Whether or not your shop keeps its full books in Forge, the everyday behavior you rely on is the same — statuses change, PO-matched bills track what has been billed against what was received, and voiding a PO-matched bill frees that quantity back up so it can be billed again later.\n\nOne thing to know: Payables runs the shop's AP only when Forge is the sole system of record. If your shop keeps its books in an outside accounting package, that package owns Accounts Payable and this module steps aside, so you never end up entering the same bills twice.\n\nThe **Accounts** and **Batches** tabs (vendor bank accounts and NACHA payment batches) are a separate add-on that stays hidden unless an administrator turns it on. See the dedicated Bank Accounts and Payment Batches modules.","sections":[]}"""
